{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17487317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17487317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:05:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"319"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/319"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.23,0.49,0.15,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"319"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71574"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/319"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"319"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57070"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"329"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24141"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24147"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24148"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37159"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71574","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71574"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 47-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a three week history of intermittent pain and swelling under the right side of his jaw. This is not always noticeable and seems to vary in size, particularly after a meal. On examination there is a soft, non-tender 3 cm swelling immediately under right mandible and some 5 cm anterior to the angle of the jaw.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT head and neck","Sialogram","Ultrasound","Plain X-ray","MRI sialography"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u0027lump\u0027 that can be felt is almost certainly the submandibular gland. The reason that it has become enlarged and apparent to the patient is probably the result of a stone in the duct causing intermittent obstruction. This will be most noticeable at mealtimes, when the rate of salivary flow increases. The symptoms and signs described in this scenario are characteristic of a submandibular duct calculus. The easiest, quickest and most convenient way of initiating any investigative process is \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasonography\u003C/strong\u003E. This investigation is usually readily available, easy to perform and no radiation or contrast material is required. It is less useful for \u0026lt;2mm stones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith conventional sialography, the duct is cannulated and contrast instilled. Whilst this investigation is not often performed today, it does provide good detail of the salivary duct anatomy and the identification of any filling defects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHigh resolution CT of the neck is now frequently used for the evaluation of salivary stones. Most stones contain sufficient calcium to be visible on non-contrast scans. This investigation could be performed in this case if ultrasonography is inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMRI sialography could be considered as an alternative to conventional sialography, particularly as it does not required duct cannulation and there is no radiation or contrast exposure. However, MRI is less readily available than other imaging tools.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlain radiology is no longer considered as a useful diagnostic tool for salivary calculi.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case the history is very suggestive of partial duct obstruction and the presence of a stone is very likely. In these circumstances ultrasonography is the most practical initial investigation and if the patient is referred for a specialist review, a CT scan may also be helpful, not just in terms of localisation, but also assessing the degree of gland distension.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most salivary duct calculi will be visible on ultrasonography"],"references":["Wilson KF, Meier JD, Ward PD. Salivary Gland Disorders. Am Fam Physician 2014; 89:882-88.","Badash I, Raskin J, Pei M, et al. Contemporary Review of Submandibular Gland Sialolithiasis and Surgical Management Options. Cureus. 2022; 14:e28147."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57070"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"319"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57070","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57070"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T16:00:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-19T16:01:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"319"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71574"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"it